After applying a patch to a tire you will spray it once it is mounted to see if there is a leak where you patched. Sometimes when your patch appears to have been unsuccessful and leaking air it actually ends up being just air caught inside the patch when you applied it. You can take the tire off the rim and you will see it continue to bubble with no pressure to leak through. Once you confirm it is just trapped air that you are seeing you can then have greater confidence in sending the customer on their way, knowing that the tire isn't just going to go flat on them.

I hate seeing things like this, just a guy trying to do his job, someone taking a photo of them making an assumption and the internet just does their thing.

Just had to vent.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/aScUxww</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[creamygreek]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Being the first and the bravest can set down the path for inspiration of future generations.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/oiS2wjk</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/20KSkvF.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Judge Kentanji Brown Jackson's daughter so proud of her mom
